node.text: Visit with Lucille the Eastern Screech Owl- since we had to cancel our Owl Prowl tonight @centerforwildlife is giving us a mini tour of their owl enclosure

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Maine Beer Company in Primo Restaurant with @primorestaurant. May be an image of drink.

node.text: Can’t make a trip to the midcoast without getting a little Lunch for dinner.

node.accessibility_caption: The entrance to a barn dinner with lights strung through the rafters.

node.text:
Thank you to @wolfesneckcenter and @chavalmaine for a wonderful farm to table dinner last night at the Mallett Barn. Over 90% of the meal prepared by @chavalmaine was from our state, and included fruit, meat, and vegetables from Wolfe's Neck Farm as well as local cheese from @winterhillfarmer , cocktails from @nedistilling , and of course @mainebeerco beer.⁣
⁣
These dinners are a great reminder of the importance of sourcing local, and the role we play in supporting the farmers and businesses in our community.

node.accessibility_caption: The entrance to a barn dinner with lights strung through the rafters.
A menu from Chaval on a table with flowers and a yellow tablecloth
A blue Maine Beer Company camp mug in front of a large bouquet of flowers
A bartender behind the Maine Beer Company booth.
A plate of cured meats and pickled vegetables
A large bouquet of flowers
Photo by Maine Beer Company in Maine with @leavenotracecenter. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
Wherever adventure takes you this weekend from the wilderness, to local parks, even your own back yard, make sure you follow the 7 Principles of @leavenotracecenter to minimize your impact on the outdoors. ⁣
⁣
-Plan ahead and prepare.⁣
-Travel and camp on durable surfaces.⁣
-Dispose of waste properly.⁣
-Leave what you find. ⁣
-Minimize campfire impacts.⁣
-Respect wildlife.⁣
-Be considerate of other visitors. ⁣
⁣
On our travels to Maine’s islands we always bring a bag to pack out anything we have brought with us to make sure we leave things as we found them for the next visitors to experience. ⁣
⁣

node.accessibility_caption: A close up of a sweet corn and jalapeño pizza.

node.text:
We have a new pizza launching today!⁣
⁣
Sweet Corn & Jalapeño⁣
mozzarella, local corn, pickled jalapeño, vidalia onion, lime crema, cilantro

node.accessibility_caption: A brewer finishes adding hops to the dry-hop phase of a brew

node.text:
We have two new positions opening up on our job board: Full-time Brewer and Full-time Warehouse Driver.⁣
⁣
Whatever the department, Maine Beer Company is a great place to work. Our team is made up of talented individuals who share our company's commitment to community and the environment, and who are passionate about making great beer. We offer a number of great benefits including competitive pay, 401K + match, full insurance coverage, and 3 weeks paid time off. ⁣
⁣
Click on the link in our bio to learn more about our open positions and applying!

node.text:
Our Blue Crew sustainability team is at it again coming up for new uses for these large plastic barrels so they don't end up as trash. From seaweed transport for garden beds, to rainwater collection buckets, pig feeders, tables, and scrap material storage, we're finding good use for them. But perhaps nothing as good as the dog pool our friend Lyle built for his pup Julius. ⁣
⁣
If you could use a 55 gallon barrel and can pick it up here in Freeport shoot us a message at info@mainebeercompany.com and we'll make arrangements.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Maine Beer Company on July 14, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.
A bottle and snifter of Black Barn Program No. 23 sits overlooking the Maine Beer Company tasting room.

node.text:
Surprise, Black Barn Program No. 23 DIPA is here a few days early! We had a change in our packaging schedule so it is available on draft and in bottles exclusively from our tasting room starting today. If you had planned on joining us Friday for the release, don't worry there will still be plenty. ⁣
⁣
Black Barn Program No. 23 is a Double IPA we brewed just for summer using Strata, Idaho 7, and Amarillo hops. It features @blueoxmalthouse Rye and Vienna malts, because in the words of our brewer Geoff, rye not? This 8.5% DIPA has upfront tropical aromas of mango followed by notes of grapefruit and tangerine, and finishes with underlying notes of caramel, pine and onion/garlic. Enjoy!

node.text: We’ve got a solution for that case of the Mondays.

node.accessibility_caption: A bottle of Prince Percy Pilsner is held over a lobster boil.

node.text: Tell us you’re in Maine, without telling us you’re in Maine.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Maine Beer Company in Freeport, Maine. May be an image of lake and nature.
A pint of Prince Percy Pilsner sits in the rain under an orange umbrella.

node.text:
Well it’s a busy start to the weekend with Elsa visiting from the south and taking up our outdoor tables. Thank you for your patience as we work to get everyone in and to keep you dry. ⁣
⁣
The good news, they’re calling for clear skies the rest of the weekend, and the drafts are flowing with a tiny beautiful something, Another One, Dinner, Lunch, Peeper, Post Ride Snack, and Prince Percy!

node.accessibility_caption: A label for Maine Beer Company Black Barn Program No. 23 Double IPA.

node.text:
Black Barn Program No. 23 DIPA is coming! While pale ales and IPAs are our forte, we like to try out some DIPA recipes from time to time. Black Barn Program No. 23 is a 8.5% ABV Double IPA featuring Amarillo, Idaho 7, and Strata hops, and is the first time we have used Strata in a production beer. The malt bill features local @blueoxmalthouse Rye and Vienna malts, and the beer has aromas of mango, grapefruit, tangerine, caramel, pine, and garlic. ⁣
⁣
Black Barn Program No. 23 DIPA will be released on draft and in bottles exclusively from our tasting room on Friday July 16th.
